%N A389789 Number of ways to write n as (2-(n mod 2))*p + q + q', where p and q are primes, and q' is the first prime after q.
%C A389789 Conjecture: (i) a(2*n+1) > 0 for all n > 4. In other words, any odd integer greater than 10 can be written as the sum of a prime and two consecutive primes.
%C A389789 (ii) a(2*n) > 0 for all n > 426. In other words, any even number greater than 853 can be written as 2*p + q + q', where p and q are primes.
%C A389789 This is a new variant of Goldbach's conjecture. It has been verified for positive integers up to 10^5.
%C A389789 It seems that the largest odd number n with a(n) = 1 is 57, and the largest even number n with a(n) = 1 is 2724.
%H A389789 Zhi-Wei Sun, <a href="/A389789/b389789.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%H A389789 Zhi-Wei Sun, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-319-68032-3_20">Conjectures on representations involving primes</a>, in: M. Nathanson (ed.), Combinatorial and Additive Number Theory II, Springer Proc. in Math. & Stat., Vol. 220, Springer, Cham, 2017, pp. 279-310.
%e A389789 a(33) = 1 with 3 + prime(6) + prime(7) = 3 + 13 + 17 = 33.
%e A389789 a(57) = 1 with 5 + prime(9) + prime(10) = 5 + 23 + 29 = 57.
%e A389789 a(600) = 1 with 2*83 + prime(47) + prime(48) = 2*83 + 211 + 223 = 600.
%e A389789 a(1404) = 1 with 2*229 + prime(91) + prime(92) = 2*229 + 467 + 479 = 1404.
%e A389789 a(2724) = 1 with 2*359 + prime(168) + prime(169) = 2*359 + 997 + 1009 = 2724.
%t A389789 S[n_]:=S[n]=Prime[n]+Prime[n+1];
%t A389789 tab={};Do[r=0;k=1;Label[bb];If[S[k]>=n,Goto[aa]];If[PrimeQ[(n-S[k])/(2-Mod[n,2])],r=r+1];k=k+1;Goto[bb];
%t A389789 Label[aa];tab=Append[tab,r],{n,1,100}];Print[tab]
